# Fluff Date: 2026-02-21 18:07:19
overview:<p>The Guillotine was first designed in 2499 by Newhart Industries as a heavy shock unit for the Terran Hegemony, quickly establishing itself as one of the most reliable seventy-ton BattleMechs in the Star League Defense Force. Built to deliver devastating close-range firepower while maintaining exceptional mobility for its weight class, the Guillotine became a mainstay of SLDF heavy regiments for generations. As the march of technology produced heavier and more powerful designs, the Guillotine gradually transitioned from a front-line assault role to that of a heavy raider and harassment unit, a mission profile its speed, jump capability, and energy-heavy weapons suite made it ideally suited for.</p><p>The destruction of Newhart's New Earth factory during the Amaris Civil War in 2776 dealt a severe blow to production, though Irian BattleMechs Unlimited continued to manufacture the design under license from their facility on Irian. The technological decline of the Succession Wars forced a downgrade to the simpler GLT-4L model, but the recovery of the Helm Memory Core in the late 3040s enabled Irian to restore and ultimately surpass the original design's capabilities, ensuring the Guillotine's continued service well into the thirty-second century.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Guillotine achieves an impressive balance of firepower, protection, and mobility for a seventy-ton heavy 'Mech. Its VOX 280 engine drives the chassis to a respectable sixty-four kilometers per hour, while four Anderson 398 jump jets provide a 120-meter jump capability that allows it to exploit difficult terrain such as mountains and jungles where heavier designs cannot follow. Twelve tons of Ulston Prime armor offer protection comparable to many assault-class machines, enabling the Guillotine to absorb considerable punishment during its characteristic aggressive engagements.</p><p>The primary armament centers on a Sunglow Type 2 large laser in the left arm, backed by four ExoStar II medium lasers distributed across the arms and side torsos, and a Coventry-6 SRM-6 launcher. This energy-heavy loadout grants the Guillotine excellent sustained combat endurance with minimal logistical requirements, though the design has been plagued by persistent weapon system quirks. The Sunglow laser's fiber optic power cabling runs near the surface of the underarm and can bind when the weapon is raised above shoulder level, while the SRM launcher has a stubborn tendency to fail to arm its fifth and sixth missiles. Twenty-five single heat sinks on the original model allow the entire weapons suite to fire simultaneously with minimal heat buildup, making the Guillotine a formidable brawler despite these idiosyncrasies.</p>

deployment:<p>Introduced in 3049 following the recovery of the Helm Memory Core, this variant represents Irian BattleMechs Unlimited's effort to restore the Guillotine to its Star League-era glory. The endo steel chassis and CASE system are reinstated, and the primary weapon is upgraded to a Diverse Optics Sunbeam ER large laser, providing substantially greater effective range than the original Sunglow while finally eliminating the cable-snagging issues that had plagued the design for centuries. In virtually all other respects this variant mirrors the original GLT-3N, retaining the same armor coverage, speed profile, and secondary weapons suite. Produced from a refurbished Newhart-licensed facility on Irian and later from Angell II, this variant became the standard production Guillotine for the Clan Invasion era and beyond.</p>

history:<p>The Guillotine's combat history spans over six centuries of near-continuous service. Designed in 2499 as a front-line heavy for the Terran Hegemony, it set the standard against which later heavy BattleMechs would be measured. Known for its mobility, armor, and dependable mix of weapons, the Guillotine anchored fast attack units alongside designs like the Griffin and Thunderbolt, providing heavy fire support for entire companies. With the rise of the Star League, the design became a fixture of nearly every SLDF regiment, though heavier and more sophisticated machines eventually pushed it into the role of a heavy raider.</p><p>The fall of the Star League scattered Guillotines across all the Great Houses, while ComStar seized the largest intact stockpile after raiding the former Newhart facilities on New Earth in 2788, acquiring close to a battalion's worth of machines. Newhart's factory had already been destroyed in 2776 during the Amaris Civil War, leaving Irian BattleMechs Unlimited as the sole remaining producer. Lycomb-Davion IntroTech had also manufactured the Guillotine from their facility on Demeter, but Capellan Confederation forces destroyed this plant early in the First Succession War. As the Succession Wars ground on, shortages of advanced components forced Irian to develop the downgraded GLT-4L, which they produced intermittently for the next several centuries.</p><p>During the Second Succession War, House Marik employed Guillotines to devastating effect as guerrilla raiders against Capellan worlds, exploiting the design's energy-based weapons and jump capability to strike military support facilities and industries with impunity. Two dozen Guillotines ranged across half a dozen worlds, hiding in unpopulated areas and appearing at random, tying up Confederation forces until Marik troops captured the worlds of Ohrensen and Ilmachna. ComStar's stockpile fed machines to both their Com Guards and, covertly, to the Ghost Regiments of the Draconis Combine.</p><p>The recovery of the Helm Memory Core in the late 3040s breathed new life into the design. Irian's GLT-5M model, produced from a refurbished plant originally established under a Newhart license, not only restored the Guillotine to its Star League-era capabilities but improved upon them with more reliable weaponry. The design continued to evolve through the FedCom Civil War, which saw the introduction of the Federated Suns' GLT-8D refit, and the Jihad, when Irian Technologies produced the GLT-6WB and GLT-6WB2 variants for the Word of Blake. Production has continued into the Dark Age and ilClan eras from Irian's facilities on both Irian and Angell II, with the GLT-7M representing the latest evolution of this venerable design.</p>

